While I take a breather from a whirlwind couple of days to enjoy a tragedy =
about political populism, let me share my impressions of Frieze week in Lon=
don. If art fairs had lineages, there would be two dominant families. The o=
lder, perhaps more refined, would be Art Basel, founded by Ernst Beyeler in=
 Switzerland more than 50 years ago. The upstart challenger would be Frieze=
, the scrappy contemporary art fair that grew out of a London art magazine =
and the success of the YBA movement.

Each has expanded to other cities, and they are now facing each other this =
month across the English Channel, with Frieze London this week followed sho=
rtly
thereafter by Art Basel Paris. It=E2=80=99s not clear who really wants this=
 struggle for dominance. (A competition that=E2=80=99s been complicated by =
Brexit, the abolition of the old non-dom regime, fears that France could re=
instate its wealth tax, etcetera.)

Here in London, a lot has been programmed around the Frieze fair, including=
 scores of gallery shows, important museum shows, and several satellite fai=
rs. Even so, there=E2=80=99s a sense that collectors and galleries might be=
 giving the fair a pass. Is that a function of the art market=E2=80=99s sla=
ck tide, or a secular shift away from London as the art capital of Europe?

