Art fair weeks in a foreign city are a bit like a mountaineering expedition=
, requiring careful preparation and planning. But, ultimately, they are suc=
cessful if you just keep putting one foot in front of the other. There=E2=
=80=99s always one more thing to see, one more person to say hello to, one =
more question to ask. If you=E2=80=99re not careful, it can all catch up to=
 you at the summit where you=E2=80=99re gasping for oxygen=E2=80=94and coll=
apse.

For this season=E2=80=99s cluster of shows in London, I timed my flight to =
arrive later in the day, in order to hit the ground running at the auction =
house viewings. Many galleries have shows opening later in the week; with F=
rieze on Wednesday, it seemed smart to cover the auctions as soon as practi=
cal.

Before I even made it into town, I got a call from a dealer who wanted to t=
alk a bit about the art market.
Prompted by my Sunday column ( https://puck.news/newsletter_content/a-basqu=
iat-mystery-gagosians-journal-a-market-vibe-check/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Powe=
r+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2810%2F8%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2=
810%2F1%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=
=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) about the midseason sales=E2=80=94particularly the =
46 percent of lots that were sold for prices below the estimates=E2=80=94th=
e dealer turned my attention to the effect of auction house fees on those e=
stimates. In short, he argued, works priced in the middle of the market had=
 become harder to sell at auction because of these fees, which are higher t=
han in private sales. Also, as I noted in return, prices have not really ch=
anged much over the past nine years. So anyone who bought a work of art a d=
ecade ago, and is hoping to at least recoup their investment, is forced to =
push the auction houses for an estimate
close to the full price that they previously paid, with fees. For potential=
 bidders, those numbers look very steep, which forces the consignors to low=
er their reserve when the auction finally comes. That=E2=80=99s how you get=
 nearly half the lots selling for prices below the estimate.

In fact, the best auction strategy is to offer the work at a very low estim=
ate and hope competition gets the seller to the desired price. But that str=
ategy has real risks, especially with middle-market material, and it=E2=80=
=99s better not to roll the dice and instead simply sell the work privately=
 with a lower fee structure. The point, this dealer wanted me to know, is t=
hat there are a lot more deals being done in private, where the wait is lon=
ger but the risk is lower. (We can see this in the private sales figures th=
e auction houses put out for the first half of the year, which have not dro=
pped as much as the auction totals have.)

That insight was in the back of my mind
as I arrived in London, where I had already heard about how fewer collector=
s, especially Americans, were coming to this year=E2=80=99s Frieze, and man=
y more prominent galleries were taking a pass, than in previous years. Neve=
rtheless, if my dealer friend is right, there should be far more sales acti=
vity behind the scenes than it appears on the surface.

