          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px;">
           <p style=3D"margin: 0; color: #000000; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 30px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 0;">Good evening, and welcome b=
ack to Wall Power, coming to you from the National Theatre in London as the=
 curtain rises on <b>David Oyelowo </b>in <b>Shakespeare</b>=E2=80=99s <i>C=
oriolanus</i>. <br/><br/>While I take a breather from a whirlwind couple of=
 days to <i>enjoy</i> a tragedy about political populism, let me share my i=
mpressions of Frieze week in London. If art fairs had lineages, there would=
 be two dominant families. The older, perhaps more refined, would be Art Ba=
sel, founded by <b>Ernst Beyeler</b> in Switzerland more than 50 years ago.=
 The upstart challenger would be Frieze, the scrappy contemporary art fair =
that grew out of a London art magazine and the success of the YBA movement.=
 <br/><br/>Each has expanded to other cities, and they are now facing each =
other this month across the English Channel, with Frieze London this week f=
ollowed shortly
thereafter by Art Basel Paris. It=E2=80=99s not clear who really wants this=
 struggle for dominance. (A competition that=E2=80=99s been complicated by =
Brexit, the abolition of the old non-dom regime, fears that France could re=
instate its wealth tax, etcetera.) <br/><br/>Here in London, a lot has been=
 programmed around the Frieze fair, including scores of gallery shows, impo=
rtant museum shows, and several satellite fairs. Even so, there=E2=80=99s a=
 sense that collectors and galleries might be giving the fair a pass. Is th=
at a function of the art market=E2=80=99s slack tide, or a secular shift aw=
ay from London as the art capital of Europe? <br/><br/>The question has bee=
n in the backdrop of every conversation here. I=E2=80=99ll get into that mo=
re next week, in Paris. <br/></p>
          </td>
