         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s1">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Art fair weeks in a=
 foreign city are a bit like a mountaineering expedition, requiring careful=
 preparation and planning. But, ultimately, they are successful if you just=
 keep putting one foot in front of the other. There=E2=80=99s always one mo=
re thing to see, one more person to say hello to, one more question to ask.=
 If you=E2=80=99re not careful, it can all catch up to you at the summit wh=
ere you=E2=80=99re gasping for oxygen=E2=80=94and collapse. <br/><br/>For t=
his season=E2=80=99s cluster of shows in London, I timed my flight to arriv=
e later in the day, in order to hit the ground running at the auction house=
 viewings. Many galleries have shows opening later in the week; with Frieze=
 on Wednesday, it seemed smart to cover the auctions as soon as practical. =
<br/><br/>Before I even made it into town, I got a call from a dealer who w=
anted to talk a bit about the art market.
Prompted by my Sunday <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9=
pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dTYm1vM2JQWTEwRXVJZy1Ic2ZsRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaH=
R0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvbmV3c2xldHRlcl9jb250ZW50L2EtYmFzcXVpYXQtbXlzdGVyeS1nY=
Wdvc2lhbnMtam91cm5hbC1hLW1hcmtldC12aWJlLWNoZWNrLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249V2FsbCtQ=
b3dlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODEwJTJGOCUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9V2F=
sbCtQb3dlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODEwJTJGMSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT=
1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09Z=
jZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5r=
X2lkIjoxMTI5OTAyfQ/e3e8c17cb6f2aa710bc040b713eecec539d6c0b446bfcbb04f1b8c27=
0ffab92f" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" cla=
ss=3D"sdf">column</a></u> about the midseason sales=E2=80=94particularly th=
e 46 percent of lots that were sold for prices <i>below</i> the estimates=
=E2=80=94the dealer turned my attention to the effect of auction house fees=
 on those estimates. In short, he argued, works priced in the middle of the=
 market had become harder to sell at auction because of these fees, which a=
re higher than in private sales. Also, as I noted in return, prices have no=
t really changed much over the past nine years. So anyone who bought a work=
 of art a decade ago, and is hoping to at least <i>recoup</i> their investm=
ent, is forced to push the auction houses for an estimate
close to the full price that they previously paid, with fees. For potential=
 bidders, those numbers look very steep, which forces the consignors to low=
er their reserve when the auction finally comes. That=E2=80=99s how you get=
 nearly half the lots selling for prices below the estimate.  <br/><br/>In =
fact, the <i>best</i> auction strategy is to offer the work at a very low e=
stimate and hope competition gets the seller to the desired price. But that=
 strategy has real risks, especially with middle-market material, and it=E2=
=80=99s better not to roll the dice and instead simply sell the work privat=
ely with a lower fee structure. The point, this dealer wanted me to know, i=
s that there are a <i>lot</i> more deals being done in private, where the w=
ait is longer but the risk is lower. (We can see this in the private sales =
figures the auction houses put out for the first half of the year, which ha=
ve not dropped as much as the auction totals have.)<br/><br/>That insight w=
as in the back of my mind
as I arrived in London, where I had already heard about how fewer collector=
s, especially Americans, were coming to this year=E2=80=99s Frieze, and man=
y more prominent galleries were taking a pass, than in previous years. Neve=
rtheless, if my dealer friend is right, there should be far more sales acti=
vity behind the scenes than it appears on the surface.<br/></td>
         </tr>
